   <reviews>
      <review>
         <snippet>Suspenseful, surprising, and psychologically rich.</snippet>
         <url>http://www.csmonitor.com/2005/0624/p14s02-almo.html</url>
         <critic>David Sterritt</critic>
      </review>
      <review>
         <snippet>It takes enormous skill to pull off such a high-wire act without diminishing the gravity of the situation, but Bong and his first-rate cast are up to the task.</snippet>
         <url>http://www.theavclub.com/review.php?review_id=8631</url>
         <critic>Scott Tobias</critic>
      </review>
      <review>
         <snippet>It's an altogether remarkable piece of work, deepening the genre while whipping its skin off, satirizing an entire nation's nearsighted apathy as it wonders, almost aloud, about the nature of truth, evidence, and social belonging.</snippet>
         <url>http://www.villagevoice.com/film/0525,atkinson1,65173,20.html</url>
         <critic>Michael Atkinson</critic>
      </review>
      <review>
         <snippet>What emerges is quite extraordinary.</snippet>
         <url>http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/07/28/AR2005072802188.html</url>
         <critic>Stephen Hunter</critic>
      </review>
      <review>
         <snippet>A powerful, slow-burning portrait of human fallibility.</snippet>
         <url>http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117920599?categoryid=31&amp;cs=1</url>
         <critic>Derek Elley</critic>
      </review>
      <review>
         <snippet>A haunting score and beautifully atmospheric cinematography by Kim Hyung-gu round out the achievements of this unique and engaging Korean thriller.</snippet>
         <url>http://www.filmthreat.com/Reviews.asp?Id=6377</url>
         <critic>Mariko McDonald</critic>
      </review>
      <review>
         <snippet>What distinguishes Memories of Murder, setting it apart from rank-and-file thrillers, is its singular mix of gallows humor and unnerving solemnity.</snippet>
         <url>http://movies2.nytimes.com/2005/07/15/movies/15memo.html</url>
         <critic>Manohla Dargis</critic>
      </review>
      <review>
         <snippet>Uses dark humor, incisive characterizations and social commentary to infuse its familiar detective tale with a distinctive flair.</snippet>
         <url>http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr/reviews/review_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1000988719</url>
         <critic>Frank Scheck</critic>
      </review>
      <review>
         <snippet>As exciting for its narrative twists and turns as for its Korean textures and rhythms.</snippet>
         <url>http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/07/28/AR2005072800618.html</url>
         <critic>Desson Thomson</critic>
      </review>
      <review>
         <snippet>Becomes something of a rainswept Korean koan on both the nobility and futility of persistence in the face of obviously insurmountable odds.</snippet>
         <url>http://www.austinchronicle.com/gyrobase/Calendar/Film?Film=oid%3A270447</url>
         <critic>Marc Savlov</critic>
      </review>
      <review>
         <snippet>The script is as sloppy as Song's unkempt cop, sprinkled with intriguing ideas and imaginative details that, like the investigation, simply get lost in blind alleys.</snippet>
         <url>http://seattlepi.nwsource.com/movies/227860_limited10.html</url>
         <critic>Sean Axmaker</critic>
      </review>
